{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:06:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:06:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18051"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18051"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.03,0.07,0.17,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73402"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10765"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58871"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73402"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe humerus is a long bone in the upper arm, and its surgical neck is a common site for fractures (Image). This area is particularly vulnerable to injury due to its anatomical location and the structures that pass nearby.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most at risk of injury with a fracture at this site?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary nerve","Median nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA fracture of the surgical neck of the humerus most commonly endangers the \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. This nerve wraps around the humerus near the surgical neck and can be damaged in such fractures, leading to deltoid muscle weakness and sensory loss over the lateral shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve is more commonly associated with mid-shaft humeral fractures.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve is located near the elbow and is not typically affected by humeral neck fractures.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve runs along the arm but is not closely associated with the surgical neck of the humerus.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve primarily innervates the anterior compartment of the arm and is not at risk in surgical neck fractures.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The surgical neck of the humerus is a common site for fractures, especially in older adults.","The axillary nerve and the posterior circumflex humeral artery are closely associated with the surgical neck of the humerus.","Injury to the axillary nerve can result in weakness of the deltoid muscle and loss of sensation over the lateral shoulder."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58871"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18051"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21356"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21356"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ka3VRDjBzluRFDC7tbpoa8XHCiVExE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ka3VRDjBzluRFDC7tbpoa8XHCiVExE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":615,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58871"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T19:10:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T19:11:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10765"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73402"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedA